A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out Gaudi’s interiors
The roof mutes like the back of a prehistoric oak, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are broken fish columns.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splitters and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of shelves and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi’s youth style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, gentle colors and textures that resemble nature and living things.
It is only with a closer look that you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire facade looks even more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the brightness of the colors.
The same swinging lines and enclosed shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Shaft-shaped wood copies the window frames, shelves, decorative elements of doors, and even locking holes and railings.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the bustling shopping street Passeig de Gràcia No. 43 was created by the renovation of a house from 1877, carried out by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally consisted of the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately agreed to Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and even cheaper reconstruction.
However, the rental house Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on its zipper that the decorations were created for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and also the use of mosaics on the façade was his idea.
However, many other painters and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also took part in the construction of Gaudí’s Casa Milá in the Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms due to the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "apparent house".
It is also said that the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed for the house a unique central heating system for the time with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
It's a strange thing about her 45-degree inclination.
In his creation, Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be confused by them.
Prior to the construction, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he had made about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so dismayed with the result that they demanded repairs two years later.
The councillors also insisted that the construction, with its pillars, even intervened on the public road.
However, there were no changes, quite the opposite - only fifteen days after the request of the district in this regard, Josep Batlló submitted an application for the approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The house owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a company hall, on the 3rd floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was sold to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the rooftop terrace.
The basic elements of the reconstruction have removed all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked on a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors, so that a larger society can be conveniently plagiarized without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house also received a rather unusual roof and two other floors through Gaudí’s remodeling, in addition to a new façade.
Also impressive is Gaudí’s play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the lighthouses.
The game of these two colors gives a maximum of light to all floors of the house.
In doing so, he simply used the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló House, which was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The owners of the house decided to take this step only in the year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly tolerant business, the visits were kept in place, yes, they were extended to other common areas and the attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard style, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards will get a 20% discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the true atmosphere of the house with its dragon tower, you should try to make friends with one of the homeowners and visit him at home.
