A longer finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of getting cancer.
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially when there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues tracked more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer in Britain, but also 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
In more than half of the study participants, the right finger was shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were equal in length.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, and in men up to sixty even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are already formed in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer finger.
Previous research has revealed that just testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said <0xC4><0x8C>TK knew this study volatilely, yet he did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be “completely proven.”
