However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region’s most populous countries, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
Approximately 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a marked increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America’s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
