"This organism has two options."
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
“That makes it something very special, even though it’s almost a kind of ‘foreign’ way of life,” said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online issue of Science on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as scientists found out, the bacterium in California’s Mono Lake grows even further when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"You're wondering what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the report from Arizona State University.
Discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were announced gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could act on the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery “shows that organisms in other planetary systems can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the ‘standard elements’ that we think are absolutely vital are not necessarily defined,” said Charles Cockell, professor at the University of Verrichten at the Planetary and Space Sciences Institute of Keenenen.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not a coincidence.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose the Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically identical, she assumed that microbes exposed to both may be able to replace one element with another.
“The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to its chemically similar behavior to phosphorus.”
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it lubricates almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the GFAJ-1 bacterium to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adjusted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can also survive in arsenic, showing that an arsenic-based form of life can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic occurs more frequently.
According to Jamie S. Foster, professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has been no working example.
Arsene occurred more frequently in the early Earth years, she says, which is why science has assumed that early life forms have used it.
"This gives us reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than in the early Earth age," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simons' research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
