It is assumed that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her public service.
On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany adopts a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the preservation of the old-fashioned traditions of most of its partners.
Given the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways to get out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South had to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German mark – although it is now more like Science Fiction – is supported by a majority of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is a restructuring of the euro in accordance with German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; penalisation of countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the payment of some countries, as well as the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to private sectors.
The German position is unambiguous and has been distinguished for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government withdrew a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of a conflict between what Germany deemed necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign put the Central European country, when Merkel painfully pushed out the decision to save Greece.
At the time, this was heavily criticized, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the public opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel is re-emerging with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union agreements to allow the rescue of a country, while at the same time obliged private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European as it drives the Irish crisis and everything else.
But their proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which is to enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that is not meant to be crossed.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures need to be taken now - the old way of functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the birth year of a new monetary area, in which counter-trading countries can be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector must take part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to hit a hard pace of growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external economic balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as indicated by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do bad to not understand it.
It is not just about lowering the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheating on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by the spring of 2013.
It seems that Zapatero has understood that, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, she has the hypothesis of creating order in her own home.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn’t look like it would change anything.
Among the possibilities envisaged is that we should not exclude the euro area, which is completely blocked by less-reliable countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
