The U.S. is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must present themselves with the visa application offices before they speak to the consulate; the costs will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa in the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the Visa Application Services (ASC, the initial letters in English) prior to their interview with the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be checked by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new method has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately the termination language, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is delivered.
The applicant only makes a single payment that covers the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of <0x24>140 for a tourist visa, <0x24>150 for visa applications (including visas for time workers) and <0x24>390 for traders and investors.
Those who just want to extend their visa do not have to have a conversation at the consulate, they only have to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and take their fingerprints.
As the biometric data is collected in the ASC, the applicants who need a second appointment for the consultation at the consulate will remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo are no longer required to pay the <0x24>26 service allowance.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visa-FAQs.html
